'''Olfactophilia''' or '''osmolagnia''' is a [[paraphilia]] for, or [[sexual arousal]] by, smells and odors emanating from the body, especially the sexual areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/GESUND/ARCHIV/SEN/CH20.HTM#b1-PARAPHILIAS|title=Paraphilias|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525235330/http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/GESUND/ARCHIV/SEN/CH20.HTM#b1-PARAPHILIAS|archivedate=2013-05-25|df=}} This webpage cites the source: Money, John. ''Lovemaps: Clinical Concepts of Sexual/Erotic Health and Pathology, Paraphilia, and Gender Transposition in Childhood, Adolescence, and Maturity''. Buffalo, N.Y.: Prometheus Books, 1986 {{ISBN|0-87975-456-7}}</ref> [[Sigmund Freud]] used the term '''''osphresiolagnia''''' in reference to pleasure caused by odors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gkEVAAAAIAAJ&q=Osphresiolagnia%20freud&dq=Osphresiolagnia%20freud&pgis=1|title=Collected Papers: Three case histories|first=Sigmund|last=Freud|date=1 January 1963|publisher=Collier Books|page=77|accessdate=20 December 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>
''Campbell's Psychiatric Dictionary'' includes them into [[parosmia]]s, disturbances of the sense of smell.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UVHpS_4qY54C&pg=PA567&lpg=PA567&dq=Osphresiolagnia+freud&source=web&ots=6lyqIjqsao&sig=qU5wpFZPjeJ1F9IapF2IAOW1DiA&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=6&ct=result#PPA483,M1 Campbell R.J. (2004), ''Campbell's Psychiatric Dictionary''. New York: Oxford University Press. p. 483]</ref>
==Etymology== * ''olfactophilia'' – Latin ''olfacto'', to smell, pertaining to the sense of smell, and Greek ''philia'', "love" * ''osmolagnia'' – Greek ''osme'', "smell", and ''lagneia'', "lust"
